# Text Overlap Prevention

## Critical: Calculate Bounds Before Placing Text

Every text element occupies vertical space. Before positioning, calculate the **bounding box** and ensure minimum clearance between adjacent elements.

### WordLine positioning
`WordLine` uses `transform: translateY(-50%)` — the `y` prop is the **vertical center**, not the top edge.

| Property | Top edge | Bottom edge |
|----------|----------|-------------|
| WordLine | `y - fontSize * 0.6` | `y + fontSize * 0.6` |
| Raw text div (top) | `top` | `top + fontSize * 1.2` |
| Raw text span (centered) | depends on parent | parent top + fontSize * 1.2 |

### Minimum clearance rules
- **Between two text blocks**: `max(fontSize_upper, fontSize_lower) * 0.5` minimum gap
- **Between text and decorative line**: `fontSize * 0.4` minimum gap
- **Between text and card/container edge**: `fontSize * 0.3` minimum padding
- **Between scene title and content below**: at least `80px` at 4K (3840×2160)

### Example calculation
```
WordLine y=980, size=120:
  top  = 980 - 120*0.6 = 908
  bottom = 980 + 120*0.6 = 1052

WordLine y=1120, size=120:
  top  = 1120 - 120*0.6 = 1048
  bottom = 1120 + 120*0.6 = 1192

Gap = 1048 - 1052 = -4  ← OVERLAP! Increase y gap.
Fix: Move second line to y=1140 → top=1068, gap=16px (still tight).
Better: y=1160 → top=1088, gap=36px ✓
```

## Scene Transitions: Never Leave Scenes Fully Opaque

`SceneFade` with `fadeOut={0}` means the scene stays at **full opacity** when the next scene starts. This causes both scenes to render simultaneously during the overlap window.

### Rules
1. **Always set `fadeOut` to at least 10** unless the scene has an explicit visual exit (typography flood, vortex burst, etc.)
2. If the scene has an explicit exit effect, **fade out all other content** during that effect (wrap in an opacity container)
3. Adjacent `<Sequence>` overlaps (e.g., `from={115}` starting before previous scene's `from + dur`) must have corresponding fade-out/fade-in to create a crossfade

### Pattern: Typography flood exit
```tsx
const textFadeOut = floodRaw > 0 ? Math.max(0, 1 - floodRaw * 3) : 1;
// Wrap all text in: <div style={{ opacity: textFadeOut }}>...</div>
// The flood text itself handles its own opacity via floodOpacity
```

## Transition Elements Must Be the Existing Element, Not a Duplicate

When an on-screen element (e.g. a word, card, icon) is used as a transition effect (scaling up, flying out, morphing), **animate the existing element** — never create a second copy.

### The Duplicate Anti-Pattern
```tsx
// ❌ BAD: creates a second "2015." on top of the one already in the headline
<WordLine words={[{text:"stuck"}, {text:"in"}, {text:"2015."}]} />
{floodActive && <span style={{scale: floodScale}}>2015.</span>}  // DUPLICATE!
```

### The Correct Pattern
```tsx
// ✅ GOOD: break the word out of WordLine so it can be individually animated
<span><BlurWord text="stuck" /></span>
<span><BlurWord text="in" /></span>
<span style={{ transform: floodActive ? `scale(${floodScale})` : normalTransform }}>
  2015.
</span>
// No duplicate — the same element transitions from inline to full-screen
```

### Rules
1. If a WordLine word needs to animate independently later, **don't use WordLine** for that word — render it manually with the same flex layout
2. The element's entrance animation and its transition animation should be on the **same DOM node** using conditional logic
3. Surrounding elements (siblings in the same row) should fade out during the transition while the transitioning element stays

## Transition Effects Must Emerge FROM Scene Elements

When a transition effect (vortex, burst, glow, merge) represents on-screen elements combining, the effect must:

1. **Only appear AFTER the elements have visibly converged** — never before or simultaneously
2. **Use ONLY the colors of the elements being combined** — never introduce new colors that aren't on screen
3. **Start small and grow proportionally** as the source elements shrink/converge
4. Surrounding content (headers, labels) should fade out as the effect takes over

### Timing rule
If elements converge over progress `0→1`, the transition effect should not become visible until at least `0.4-0.5` progress, when elements have physically overlapped at the convergence point.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD: core only forms when cards have overlapped
const CORE_THRESHOLD = 0.45;
const coreProgress = clamp01((vt - CORE_THRESHOLD) / (1 - CORE_THRESHOLD));

// ❌ BAD: core appears before convergence even starts
const vortexAppear = VORTEX_START - 10; // 10 frames too early!
```

### Color rule
```tsx
// ✅ GOOD: gradient uses only the card colors
const CARD_COLORS = [C.rose, C.amber, C.textDim];
background: `conic-gradient(${CARD_COLORS[0]}, ${CARD_COLORS[1]}, ${CARD_COLORS[2]}, ${CARD_COLORS[0]})`;

// ❌ BAD: introduces accent + cyan which aren't on any card
background: `conic-gradient(${C.rose}, ${C.accent}, ${C.cyan}, ${C.amber}, ${C.rose})`;
```

## SVG-to-HTML Element Swaps

When replacing an SVG text element with an HTML element (e.g. to add per-character styling), **the swap must be instant and pixel-aligned**.

### Rules
1. **Zero overlap frames** — the SVG element must disappear on the exact frame the HTML element appears. Never cross-fade.
2. **Match coordinate systems** — SVG `text` with `dominantBaseline="central"` at `y={CY}` renders at a different visual position than HTML `position: absolute; top: CY`. Use flexbox centering to match:
   ```tsx
   // SVG text centered at CY using dominantBaseline="central"
   <text y={CY} textAnchor="middle" dominantBaseline="central">Animly</text>

   // HTML match: center via flex, not absolute top
   <div style={{
     position: "absolute", left: 0, right: 0,
     top: 0, height: H,  // fill full height
     display: "flex", alignItems: "center", justifyContent: "center",
   }}>
     <span style={{ fontSize: 200, fontWeight: 800 }}>Animly</span>
   </div>
   ```
3. **Delay subsequent transforms** — if the HTML version will animate (tilt, scale, color), delay those transforms by 5-10 frames. The element must appear **flat and identical** to the SVG for a few frames to make the swap invisible.
4. **Opacity approach:**
   ```tsx
   // SVG: instant off
   const svgOpacity = frame >= SWAP_FRAME ? 0 : svgProgress;
   // HTML: instant on
   {frame >= SWAP_FRAME && <div>...</div>}
   ```

### Why not cross-fade?
Cross-fading reveals coordinate mismatches (even 1-2px) as a visible "jitter" or "double vision." Instant swaps are imperceptible if alignment is correct.

---

## Checklist Before Finalizing a Scene Layout

1. List every text element's y-position and font size
2. Calculate top/bottom edges using the formulas above
3. Verify gaps between adjacent elements meet minimums
4. Check that `SceneFade` has non-zero `fadeOut` (or explicit exit handling)
5. If two `<Sequence>` components overlap in time, verify crossfade behavior
6. Check that animated entrance `translateY` offsets don't cause temporary overlaps with nearby elements
7. If any SVG element is replaced by HTML mid-animation, verify zero-overlap instant swap (see SVG-to-HTML section above)
